{{Fusion devices | |name = Pegasus Toroidal Experiment |type=[[Spherical tokamak]] |image = Pegasus Toroidal Experiment (6140926094).jpg |major radius = 45 cm |minor radius = 40 cm |location= [[Madison, Wisconsin]], [[United States of American|United States]] }}
The '''Pegasus Toroidal Experiment''' is a [[Plasma (physics)|plasma]] confinement experiment relevant to [[fusion power]] production, run by the Department of Engineering Physics of the [[University of Wisconsin-Madison]]. It is a [[spherical tokamak]], a very low-aspect-ratio version of the [[tokamak]] configuration, i.e. the minor radius of the torus is comparable to the major radius.
==See also== Other spherical torus experiments: * [[National Spherical Torus Experiment]] (NSTX) * [[Mega Ampere Spherical Tokamak]] (MAST) * [[Small Tight Aspect Ratio Tokamak]] (START)
==External links== *[http://pegasus.ep.wisc.edu/ Pegasus Toroidal Experiment]
